#### What problem are you trying to solve?

The `uploadProgress` event requires splitting the request body into several chunks, as explained in the [documentation](https://github.com/sindresorhus/got/blob/main/documentation/3-streams.md#streamuploadprogress). Else, it is only emitted twice (at 0% and 100%), which makes the feature not useful for progress monitoring purposes.

> Note: To get granular upload progress instead of just 0% and 100%, split the body into chunks using the [chunk-data](https://github.com/sindresorhus/chunk-data) package:
>   chunk(buffer, chunkSize) - For buffers/typed arrays
>   chunkFromAsync(iterable, chunkSize) - For iterables (Node.js streams are async iterables)

This works when the [`body` option](https://github.com/sindresorhus/got/blob/main/documentation/2-options.md#body) is a string, buffer, TypedArray, streams, iterable or generator.

However, this does not work when the `json` or `form` option is used instead of the `body` option. That's because Got serializes the value passed by the user to a single string, without splitting it into chunks. 

```js
const response = await got('https://mockhttp.org/post', {
  method: 'POST',
  json: {"test": '.'.repeat(1e6)},
}).on('uploadProgress', progressEvent => {
  console.log(progressEvent)
})
```

```sh
$ node test.js
{ percent: 0, transferred: 0, total: 1000011 }
{ percent: 1, transferred: 1000011, total: 1000011 }
```

Users can work around this problem by: 
  - serializing the payload themselves using `JSON.serialize(body)` or `new URLSearchParams(body).toString()`, then applying `chunk()`
  - setting the `headers['Content-Type']` option explicitly
  - setting the `headers['Content-Length']` option explicitly

However, it is somewhat unexpected to have to work around this, since users might expect the `uploadProgress` event to work properly whether they use the `body` option or the `json`/`form` options.

```js
const body = Buffer.from(JSON.stringify({"test": '.'.repeat(1e6)}))
const response = await got('https://mockhttp.org/post', {
  method: 'POST',
  body: chunk(body, 1e5),
  headers: {
    'Content-Type': 'application/json',
    'Content-Length': String(body.byteLength),
  },
}).on('uploadProgress', progressEvent => {
  console.log(progressEvent)
})
```

```
{ percent: 0, transferred: 0, total: 1000011 }
{ percent: 0.09999890001209986, transferred: 100000, total: 1000011 }
{ percent: 0.19999780002419973, transferred: 200000, total: 1000011 }
